</m:math> with those found in <link target-id="fs-id1169737723572"/>, in which there was also an inductor.</para></problem></exercise>

      <exercise id="fs-id1169738012738" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id1169737787125">
          <para id="import-auto-id1169738143727">An <emphasis effect="italics">LC</emphasis> circuit consists of a <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>3</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>00</m:mtext><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext>mH</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> inductor and a <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>5</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>00</m:mtext><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mi fontstyle="italic">μF</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> capacitor. (a) Find its impedance at 60.0 Hz and 10.0 kHz. (b) Compare these values of <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>Z</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> with those found in <link target-id="fs-id1169737723572"/> in which there was also a resistor.</para></problem>
<solution id="fs-id1169736844109">
    <para id="import-auto-id1169738246107">(a) <m:math>
 
  <m:mi>529 Ω</m:mi>
 
</m:math> at 60.0 Hz, <m:math>
 
  <m:mi>185 Ω</m:mi>
 
</m:math> at 10.0 kHz</para><para id="eip-id2226884">(b) These values are close to those obtained in <link target-id="fs-id1169737723572"/> because at low frequency the capacitor dominates and at high frequency the inductor dominates. So in both cases the resistor makes little contribution to the total impedance.</para>
    </solution>
    </exercise><exercise id="fs-id1169737794135" type="problems-exercises">
